# Article 2 — The Prints That Weren't There Yet
## Damien Hirst, the Banksy Paper Edition Estate, and a Dating Problem the Numbers Solve Themselves

Damien Hirst has a documented history of backdating his work.

In March 2024 The Guardian revealed that three of his formaldehyde sculptures, presented as products of the 1990s, were fabricated in 2017. Two months later The Guardian returned: at least 1,000 of the 10,000 paintings in his NFT project The Currency, sold with assurances they were hand-created in 2016, were mass-produced by staffers on what one source described as a "Henry Ford production line" in 2018 and 2019. His lawyers did not deny either instance. Their defence was identical both times: it was Hirst's usual practice to date conceptual works according to the year they were conceived rather than the year they were produced. Artists, they said, are perfectly entitled to be inconsistent in their dating.

The formula is simple: conceive it in Year A, make it in Year B, date it Year A, sell it at Year A prices. The premium a work commands by being early in a career, early in a movement, early in a brand's trajectory — that premium is what backdating purchases. A 1990s Hirst formaldehyde sculpture commands a different price than a 2017 one. The defence acknowledges the practice. It disputes only the characterisation.

The Banksy paper print estate runs to approximately 29,000 signed and unsigned impressions across a catalogue that Banksy Explained records as running from 2002 to 2010. Damien Hirst is the Artist of Record of the Banksy enterprise. The paper print estate is his enterprise's commercial inventory. The question the numbers in the Banksy Explained chart raise — once you sit with the arithmetic long enough — is whether the same practice applies here, and whether the chart itself is the evidence.

---

The first signal is the chart's starting date.

Banksy Explained records the authenticated paper print estate as beginning in 2002. But Rude Copper — Lazarides' legendary account of negotiating his way into a meeting to see the prints — is presented in that legend as the enterprise's first official POW release. Rude Copper does not appear on Banksy Explained. Not in 2002. Not anywhere. The print that the enterprise's own mythology establishes as the commercial origin point is the front-end bracket the chart refuses to include.

Rude Copper's absence is not an oversight. It is the same logic as the Devolved Parliament omission from the 2009 Bristol Museum section. What the chart includes is what the artist's settlement terms authorised for inclusion. What the chart excludes is what fell outside those terms — either because it predates the formalised artist designation, or because its production circumstances cannot be certified under the authentication architecture that governs everything else on the chart.

The chart starts where it starts because 2002 is when the canonical identity was settled. If the prints had been produced organically by a singular anonymous artist from the beginning, the chart would start earlier. It starts exactly at the contractual partition that formalised who the artist was and what her output would be certified to include.

---

The second signal is the AP structure.

Across the paper print estate, the artist's proof allocation converges on a baseline unit of twenty-two. Not approximately twenty-two. Exactly twenty-two, on the prints where the structure is cleanest. Police Kids: twenty-two APs. Bomb Love: forty-four — two times twenty-two. NOLA: sixty-six — three times twenty-two. Girl with Balloon: eighty-eight — four times twenty-two. Four prints across a six-year span where the AP count hits exactly on a multiple of twenty-two with zero remainder.

The twenty-two baseline resolves into a distribution architecture once you examine what twenty-two is made of. One artist copy. Ten VIP allocation units — the founding investors whose access to reserved editions is the enterprise's private market structure. Eleven POW retained inventory units — the deferred commercial supply held off-market against future price appreciation. The baseline is not an arbitrary number. It is the enterprise's full distribution apparatus compressed into an AP count, present in the public record of every print where the structure was applied cleanly.

A distribution architecture this precise — encoding three-tier allocation across artist, investor, and commercial inventory — does not emerge organically from a street artist releasing prints as the demand arose. It is designed in advance of production. Designed-in-advance AP allocation structures on prints nominally dated 2003 and 2004 are inconsistent with a spontaneous operation and consistent with a pre-planned commercial vehicle that conceived its catalogue before it produced it, and dated the production to the conception.

That is the conception-date defence, applied to the paper estate before the paper estate required defending.

---

The third signal is Girl with Balloon.

Eighty-eight APs. Four times twenty-two. The hero asset of the catalogue, the image that will eventually be worth tens of millions of pounds at auction, allocated at four times the standard baseline. The arithmetic of that decision describes a treasury position. If the standard baseline holds eleven POW retained APs per print, four baselines hold forty-four — retained inventory on the single most commercially significant image in the estate, deferred against the price appreciation that the enterprise's principals could project from the founding period, realised at auction prices that by 2021 were running above £200,000 per signed AP. Forty-four retained APs at £200,000 each is £8.8 million of deferred inventory position, encoded in the AP count of a print dated 2003.

The farewell edition of Girl with Balloon — the edition of eight produced as a gift to the enterprise's insiders at the artist's departure — inverts the 88 with arithmetic precision. Four times twenty-two becomes eight. The hero asset's AP count and the farewell gift's edition size are mirror images of each other, one encoding the enterprise's maximum commercial ambition and the other encoding the artist's withdrawal from it.

---

The fourth signal is the Barely Legal uniformity.

The six prints from the 2005 Barely Legal LA exhibition carry a uniform AP count: six each. Police Kids, Morons, Grannies, Applause, Trolleys — all AP=6. The uniformity is exact across the entire set. Six is not a multiple of twenty-two. Six is the AP structure of a print where the standard allocation has been reduced to its minimum viable form: one for the artist, one for the AoR, one for POW, and three for the VIP allocation at half the standard rate.

The LA print set's AP=6 uniformity marks the moment the artist's participation in the standard allocation ends. Festival, the sixth LA print, takes thirty-nine APs and no POW run — the anomaly that encodes the contested status of the most unresolved print in the estate. Sale Ends defers its second edition by eleven years, appearing as a Version 2 in 2017. The two exceptions to the LA set's clean uniformity are the two prints where the settlement terms were most clearly in dispute. The arithmetic of the exceptions is the arithmetic of the dispute.

---

The fifth signal is Choose Your Weapon.

The last print in the pre-GDP estate — the print titled, literally, an instruction — carries an edition arithmetic that resolves to a single number across all three tiers. One hundred fifty-eight signed. Four hundred fifty colorway impressions. Fifty-eight artist's proofs. Total: six hundred sixty-six. Not approximately. Exactly. The artist signed off on the commercial paper catalogue with the number of the beast to the unit, distributed across three allocation tiers whose sum is exact. That is not a coincidence of arithmetic. It is the artist naming what she thought the enterprise had become, embedded in the last print she authorised before the GDP phase began without her.

---

The Kate Moss colorway structure resolves into the same AP logic. Twelve artist's proofs across six colorways: two per colorway, one for the artist and one for POW. The colorways are AP analogues — each variant carrying its own minimal allocation in the same two-party structure the baseline AP encodes at full scale. That colorway structure, recorded with precision on the site in 2021, is now at the centre of the Ant and Dec High Court fraud proceedings. The ledger was ahead of the litigation by five years.

The Napalm/Serpentine edition carries the clearest post-schism statement. The standard box set of fifty prints carries twenty-nine artist's proofs. Twenty-nine does not resolve into a multiple of twenty-two. It resolves into the standard baseline minus the AoR's allocation — the residual from a full allocation that has had the AoR's expected share removed before publication. The artist encoded her post-schism condition directly into the AP count. Twenty-nine only makes sense with Hirst outside the fifty.

The paper print estate was conceived during the brand's founding phase. The AP allocation architecture was designed — and could only have been designed — by people who understood they were building a commercial vehicle whose backend value would be realised over a decade or more. If the conception date is what goes on the work, the prints are dated correctly. If the production date is what the market understands when it buys a 2003 Banksy screenprint, the prints are dated the same way The Currency was dated, and the same way the formaldehyde sculptures were dated, and the defence, if it comes, will be the same defence.

Usual practice.

The twenty-two baseline. The eighty-eight APs. The six hundred sixty-six. The twenty-nine. The numbers were always there. They were waiting for someone to count them.

