# Article 3 — The Canvas Editions and the Studio That Made Them
## What Banksy Explained Records as Editions, and What the Terminus Tells You

The Banksy Explained canvas editions section opens with a number that requires no interpretation: eighteen. Eighteen canvas editions across the enterprise's commercial peak, from 2000 through 2005, documented in a chart whose column structure — title, date, edition size — is as clean and orderly as a stock ledger. Which is exactly what it is.

A stock ledger is produced by the party that holds the stock. The party that holds the Banksy canvas edition inventory is not a solitary street artist who happened to build an archive of his own work. The party that holds the inventory is the commercial entity that commissioned the production, documented the output, and controls the authentication apparatus that converts documentation into market value. The chart's clarity is corporate clarity. Its orderliness is inventory orderliness. The eighteen canvas editions recorded on Banksy Explained are the commercial layer of a fine art operation that the enterprise built alongside the street art programme that made the brand famous.

The two operations are not the same operation. Understanding the difference between them is the condition for understanding what the canvas editions actually are.

---

The canvas editions occupy three tiers by edition size. Editions of ten are the smallest: Heaven and Hell, Gangsta Rat, Happy Chopper, Bomb Middle England, and Christ with Shopping Bags. Five works — the rarest tier, priced accordingly, the editions that will command the highest individual lot values at auction as the supply is progressively absorbed. Editions of fifteen sit in the middle: Crude Oil, Bomb Love, Rude Copper, Love Is In The Air 2003, I Fought The Law, Flying Copper, Di-Faced Tenners, and Weston Super Mare. Eight works — the commercial centre of the canvas catalogue, volume enough to seed multiple markets, scarcity enough to sustain price. Editions of twenty-five occupy the broadest tier: Naked Policemen, Pulp Fiction, Turf War, and Forgive Us Our Trespassing. Four works — the most widely distributed, the most accessible price points, the editions that built the secondary market's floor.

The tiering is not arbitrary. Editions of ten, fifteen, and twenty-five describe three distinct market strategies deployed across one catalogue. The rarest tier holds the works with the most politically concentrated imagery — Christ with Shopping Bags, Bomb Middle England — and the iconography most tightly associated with the fine art practice rather than the street vocabulary. The broadest tier holds the works most legible as pop cultural objects — Pulp Fiction, Naked Policemen — whose wide distribution built the crossover audience that made the paper print programme viable at scale. The middle tier is the commercial spine. You don't arrive at this three-tier structure organically. You design it.

---

The most consequential marker in the chart is what it stops at.

The canvas editions section of Banksy Explained ends in 2005. The paper print catalogue continues to 2010. The canvas editions chart does not. The gap between 2005 and the enterprise's operational wind-down — five years of the brand's most commercially successful period, from Barely Legal through Beautiful Inside My Head Forever — contains no canvas editions.

The 2005 terminus is not a production decision by a singular artist who happened to stop making canvases. It is the boundary of the artist's settlement terms as they govern what POW can authenticate and list. What the artist certified as her canvas production for the commercial catalogue ends in 2005. What POW produced after that point either falls outside the artist's certification or falls into the hand-finished print category — the works that occupy the boundary between paper and canvas classifications, whose authenticity claims are correspondingly more complicated.

The Love Is In The Air 2006 omission sharpens the terminus precisely. Love Is In The Air appears in the canvas editions chart as a 2003 work, edition of fifteen. A second version — the CCCP Love Is In The Air — circulates in the market attributed to 2006. The 2006 version is not on the chart. The chart holds the 2003 version as the canonical object. The 2006 version is the pre-canonical committee-era work product that the chart's taxonomy excludes by not including any canvas editions after 2005 — a boundary that, held consistently, quarantines the committee-era production on the correct side of the artist's certified output.

---

Rude Copper opens and closes the canvas catalogue simultaneously.

Lazarides' foundational legend — the story he has told publicly and repeatedly about negotiating his way into a meeting to see the prints — names Rude Copper as the object of that meeting, the first official POW release, the print around which the gallery relationship was negotiated. Rude Copper appears in the canvas editions chart as an edition of fifteen. So far consistent.

But Rude Copper also carries hand-finishing marks that the chart's otherwise clean production record does not replicate across the rest of the canvas editions. The hand-finishing is consistent with a production circumstance that predates the chart's standardised three-tier structure — a proof-of-concept made before the production apparatus was fully constituted. The legend names it as the origin. The hand-finishing marks it as the anomaly. The chart includes it but cannot fully domesticate it.

The 2005 unique — the oil-painted bouquet — is the other anomaly. Not an edition. One object. Oil paint rather than the stencil-approximating hand-applied media that constitutes the artist's documented technique. The unique sits in the chart as the single confirmed instance of the artist's hand working in a mode that is unambiguously fine art. Its presence in an otherwise orderly commercial inventory is the artist's signature on the ledger — one object, one medium, one undeniable instance of the hand that made everything else.

---

The canvas editions chart is a settlement document. It records what the enterprise agreed to certify as the artist's canvas production during the period of the original deal. It stops where the settlement terms stop. It includes Rude Copper because the legend requires it. It excludes the 2006 CCCP version because the 2005 terminus requires that exclusion. It includes the 2005 unique because the settlement terms require the artist's signature on the ledger and one oil-painted bouquet is the minimum viable signature.

Eighteen works. Three tiers. One terminus. One signature. The ledger was complete before the first print in it was publicly sold.

