# Article 4 — What Banksy Explained Calls Originals
## The Pfaff Studio, the Oil-Painted Bouquet, and the One Work the Chart Cannot Categorise

The originals section of Banksy Explained is the most consequential part of the site. Not because it contains the most entries — it doesn't — but because of what its categories reveal about who built the chart and what they were authorised to include.

The site's originals taxonomy works by exclusion as much as inclusion. Understanding what the chart places in the originals category, and understanding what it places elsewhere despite being physically present at the same exhibitions, is the condition for understanding what the chart is actually documenting. Article One established the most legible instance of that exclusion logic: the six Barely Legal print-set canvases installed at the same exhibition as the works in the originals section, physically present on the same gallery walls, but taxonomically separated into the commercial editions column. The separation is not about physical medium. Both categories contain paintings on canvas. The separation is about who produced them and under what terms.

The originals column holds what the artist certified as her singular works. The commercial editions column holds what the enterprise produced using the Banksy brand's visual vocabulary. The site draws that distinction with the precision of someone who knows exactly which works fall on which side of the line, because they drew the line.

---

The Pfaff studio photographs are the originals section's evidentiary infrastructure.

James Pfaff's function in the enterprise is the documentation of canonical objects for provenance purposes. He does not photograph the street work — that is Lazarides' function. He photographs the works that require authentication: the objects whose value depends on their status as singular, certified, verifiable originals. Without the studio photograph, there is no provenance chain. Without the provenance chain, the originals section cannot function as a commercial instrument.

The works in the Pfaff studio photographs share a consistent visual grammar: controlled environments, prepared backgrounds, controlled lighting that eliminates the ambient irregularities of the street or the gallery install. The conditions are repeatable. The photograph series constitutes a controlled documentation exercise rather than an artist's personal archive — the kind of documentation exercise that a commercial operation commissions when it needs to establish provenance for a body of work that will be authenticated, valued, and offered at auction.

The originals in the Pfaff photographs are the authentic output of the artist's hand working in her trompe l'oeil practice — the hand-applied media that approximates the visual appearance of stencilled spray paint, with the organic irregularities and painterly marks that industrial stencil production cannot replicate. What the Pfaff photographs document is the fine art output of a trompe l'oeil painter working within the Banksy graphic vocabulary. The studio that produced the documentation is not the artist's studio. It is the enterprise's provenance apparatus, applied to works the artist produced independently and delivered for documentation under the terms of her commercial arrangement.

---

The 2005 unique is the originals section's most precisely calibrated entry.

One work. Oil paint. Not the trompe l'oeil technique that characterises the rest of the artist's documented output in the Banksy context, but oil paint applied to canvas in the mode of fine art painting — a bouquet of flowers, in a medium that requires no stencil reference and no visual grammar borrowed from the street.

The 2005 unique is the artist's signature on the commercial ledger, placed in the year that precedes the LA print run that will trigger the schism. It is the one work in the originals section that is unambiguously the artist's hand in a mode the enterprise could not have produced without her. Everything else in the originals section is theoretically reproducible by the enterprise's production apparatus given sufficient skill and instruction. The oil-painted bouquet is not. It requires the painter, in the room, in oil, in the mode that is hers alone.

Its placement in 2005 — the year of Barely Legal, the year before the LA print run violation that initiates the artist's withdrawal — is not arbitrary. The signature is in the right place.

---

The originals section omits what it cannot authenticate.

The 2009 Bristol Museum show presents the clearest case. The site hedges explicitly — "Selected Originals on Exhibit" — flagging a partial record that appears nowhere else in the site's exhibition coverage. The hedge is the tell. The site knows which Bristol works are in the originals column and which are not, and it cannot present the Bristol coverage as a complete originals record without the hedge because the show contained works that do not qualify under the authentication terms that govern the column.

Devolved Parliament is absent from the 2009 Bristol section. The Bristol show contained a canvas of that composition. But the canvas shown at Bristol originated as a super-sized giclee print on canvas, struck from a smaller painting and comprehensively overpainted by the art department as a room-filling exhibition prop. It met the display requirements of a major museum show. It did not meet the authentication requirements of the originals column. When a comprehensively reworked version appeared as Devolved Parliament at Sotheby's ten years later for nearly £10 million, the gap between the 2009 prop and the 2019 auction lot was already in the public record, available to anyone who had noticed that the Bristol hedge was there.

---

The originals section's double function is its most precise structural feature.

It documents the artist's certified output for authentication and provenance. That is the commercial function. But it also documents the boundary of what the enterprise is authorised to certify — which works are on the right side of the line and which are hedged, which studio photographs establish provenance and which are absent because the work they would document is not in the originals column.

The boundary is drawn with the knowledge of someone who was present when the terms were set. The hedges are placed by someone who knows which works require hedging. The 2005 unique is placed by someone who understands its function as a signature.

The chart tells you what was agreed. The gaps tell you what wasn't.

