# Article 6 — Two Studios, Two Functions
## The Photography Credit Sequence, the Blur Album Cover, and What the Banksy Publishing Record Hides in Plain Sight

Every corporate origin story has a moment when the founding arrangement stops being what it was and becomes something else. For the Banksy enterprise, that moment is legible in a photography credit — or rather, in the precise sequence of when one photographer's name appears and another's doesn't.

The Banksy publishing record runs in four stages. First: Banging Your Head Against a Brick Wall, the zine-format debut that established the visual grammar of the brand — street interventions, wall pieces, the gonzo verité of a lone operator working at night in cities that didn't ask for him. Steve Lazarides is credited. James Pfaff is not. Second: Existencilism, the first hardback, the move from zine culture into legitimate art publishing, where Lazarides appears among the additional photographers and Pfaff again does not. Third: Cut It Out, where Pfaff's name appears for the first time alongside Lazarides. Fourth: Wall and Piece, the consolidated volume that became the canonical Banksy monograph, where both men carry the same "additional photographer" designation, side by side, as though they had always occupied equivalent positions.

They had not. The sequence of their credits is one of the cleaner pieces of evidence for what the Banksy enterprise actually was, and what it was in the process of becoming.

---

Lazarides' foundational role is locked by a single object that has nothing to do with Banksy directly.

The cover photograph for Blur's Think Tank, released in 2003, is his only trademarked image. A photographer who trademarks one photograph trademarks the one that matters most — the one that established his market position, the one attached to a cultural object of sufficient value to be worth protecting. Think Tank was Blur's most critically acclaimed late-period record. Lazarides' cover photograph was the image that accompanied that moment into the world. The trademark is his declaration of what he was: a photographer of cultural consequence, present at significant moments, with the access and the eye to document them.

He had that access because of who he was in the Bristol rave scene of the late 1990s, and who he was to Jefferson Hack. Hack co-founded Dazed and Confused in 1991 and by 1998 had built it into the editorial infrastructure through which the British art world's emerging generation moved its images and ideas. Lazarides contributed to Dazed from 1998 to 2002, and freelanced for Hack's wider editorial circle — Steve Beale at Sleaze Nation, the network of publications that constituted the cultural press of the period. He sold street art photography to Thrasher, Juxtapoz, The Face. Three publications, three countries, three distinct market segments. He paid his own bills through the work itself. He was a working-class Bristol rave-scene photographer who built his position through what his camera produced.

That is why he was picked. Not despite being an outsider, but because of it. The enterprise needed a public face whose street credibility was the real thing, because the thing they were building required real street credibility to be believed. Hirst and Hack, building their joint venture, understood that a face like theirs would not do the job that a face like Lazarides' could. He was the photographer who could stand in front of street art and be believed as the photographer who documented a solitary anonymous artist. That belief was the foundation the brand required.

---

Pfaff is the other photographer, and his function is the opposite of Lazarides'.

Where Lazarides produces the legend — the street documentation that builds the public myth, the images that travel from Bristol to Thrasher to Juxtapoz and seed the brand into the global networks the enterprise needed to reach — Pfaff produces the asset. His studio sessions are controlled, inventory-focused, repeatable. Controlled backgrounds. Controlled lighting. Conditions that eliminate the ambient irregularities of the street or the gallery install and replace them with the provenance documentation that the commercial market requires before it will value a work at the prices the enterprise needs it to reach.

Without the Lazarides photograph, there is no legend. Without the Pfaff photograph, there is no provenance. Without the legend, the asset is worthless. Without the provenance, the asset cannot be sold. The enterprise required both functions from the beginning, which is why both photographers were working from the beginning. The credit sequence records when it became convenient for the second function to be publicly visible — which is not the same as when it began.

Pfaff's credits appear in Cut It Out and Wall and Piece. The canvas editions he documented are dated 2000 through 2005. A photographer credited from the third publication onward is documenting works that predate his public credit by up to four years. The documentation of those earlier works exists — it has to exist, because the authentication chain for the canvas editions requires it. The documentation predates the credit. The credit sequence is the public appearance of a function that was always there, made visible at the moment the commercial apparatus required the documentation to be traceable. This is the same logic as the AP backdating argument in Article 2. The provenance infrastructure was in place before it appeared in print.

---

The Existencilism tell is the most elegant piece of evidence in the credit sequence.

Existencilism is the first Banksy publication to appear in hardback — the move into legitimate art publishing, the step that takes the brand from zine culture into the institutional frame that serious collectors and gallerists required. Lazarides is credited as additional photographer. Pfaff is not. But Existencilism contains something that Banging Your Head Against a Brick Wall does not: Bernie Reid's stencil art, reproduced alongside the street work in a way that presents Reid's practice as continuous with the Banksy vocabulary rather than as a separate artist's output.

Reid is the lead curator of Glasgow Peace Is Tough, 2001. He is the Scottish artist credited on the Untitled 06 edition. He is one of three co-equal contributors to the enterprise's founding creative layer — Lazarides as photographer, McKenzie as the trompe l'oeil hand, Reid as the stencil practice — before the corporate pivot consolidated the brand under a singular artist identity. His stencil art appears in Existencilism because at the point of Existencilism's production the enterprise is still operating on the three-contributor model. The singular artist identity has not yet been fully formalised. The publication records the pre-canonical collaborative structure in the visual material it reproduces, without naming it as such.

The May 2002 contractual partition — the event that narrows the artist designation to McKenzie in consultation with Hirst as AoR — falls after Existencilism and before the next publication. The credit sequence and the publication content together record the transition from the three-contributor founding model to the formalised singular artist structure. The publishing record is the corporate timeline made visible as a bibliography.

---

The Lazarides arc closes at Julien's.

In late 2024, Lazarides consigned portions of his remaining Banksy collection through Julien's Auctions. Rivers Threadneedle, the most recent vehicle in the Lazarides network, enters liquidation in February 2025. LazInc itself had gone into liquidation through the same process. The arc from Think Tank cover photographer to gallery director to Julien's consignor to liquidation is the arc of someone who was given a seat at a table built by others, operated at the level of that seat until the table was cleared, and ended with the scraps of what the table once held.

The two publications he produced post-separation — Outsiders in 2009 and Banksy Captured in 2019 — fit the NDA timeline with the precision of a ten-year lock. Outsiders appears at the ten-year mark from when his involvement began in earnest. Banksy Captured appears at the twenty-year mark. The clearances required for Banksy Captured — the shots that made it through the publication process, and the image that closes the book, approved by the relevant parties — are the approval process of a separated partner working within the terms of what his separation agreement permits him to publish.

He did not own the legend he helped build. He photographed it. The trademark on the Think Tank cover is the one thing in the visual record that he can point to and say: this is mine. The rest of it — the Banksy street documentation, the archive he built from 1999 to 2008, the gallery relationships and the book credits and the cultural position — belonged to the enterprise. He was the outside photographer. The enterprise was the inside operation. The credit sequence always knew the difference, even when the public record couldn't see it clearly enough to read it.

---

Two functions. Two photographers. One public record.

Lazarides photographs the street work and builds the legend. Hack determines where that documentation is published and in what context — the publicity ran through Dazed, not through Laz. The images go through Lazarides' camera onto Hack's pages. Lazarides is the lens. Hack is the editorial infrastructure that turns the lens output into the brand's cultural position.

Pfaff photographs the studio work and builds the provenance. The asset has a price because the legend built the demand. The legend has a distribution because Hack built the channel. The provenance has a chain because Pfaff built the documentation. Three functions, three people, one enterprise.

The singular anonymous artist is the output of that enterprise. The credit sequence is the enterprise's self-description, written in the minimum visibility required to function commercially, available to anyone willing to read it in the right order.

